article.headline: Storm have won seven of eight
article.linkText: Seattle storms into break with big win
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Before becoming Olympic opponents, Sue Bird and
Lauren Jackson put together one last winning performance as
teammates.

Jackson scored 25 points and Bird had 16 to lead the Seattle
Storm to an 87-55 victory over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday night
in the last WNBA game before the league takes a monthlong break to
allow its players to participate in the Athens Games.

Jackson, who will suit up for Australia in Greece, was dominant
inside and out. The WNBA MVP grabbed eight rebounds to lead the
Storm (17-8), who have won seven of eight.

"I was a little afraid we might be distracted coming in,"
Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "Right away, I knew we were focused
and playing well."

Seattle used a 17-1 run late in the first half to build a 46-26
lead at the break. Jackson scored six during the surge and led all
scorers at the break with 13 and five rebounds.

Seattle shot a season-high 61 percent from 3-point range
(11-for-18). Bird was 4-for-6 and Jackson was 3-for-5 from behind
the arc.

Bird, along with the Sting's Dawn Staley, will play for the
United States in Athens.

"If we would have lost, it would have been difficult and you
don't want to sit with that," Bird said. "We were aggressive and
this was a good end to the first part of the season."

The WNBA All-Stars will play the U.S. National team Thursday
night in New York.

Reserve Nicole Powell tied a career high with 14 points and
Charlotte Scott-Richardson added nine for the Sting. The Sting's
five starters combined for just 22 points, on just eight of 22
shooting.

"Lauren is probably the best player in the world, so it was
just one of those nights," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "I
definitely won't be watching this game tape."

Charlotte has lost six of eight heading into the break and are
winless in four games in Seattle. The 87 points allowed was a
season-high for the Sting, surpassing the 82 allowed at Los Angeles
June 9.

Seattle was almost flawless in the first half, committing zero
turnovers and out-rebounding the Sting 21-7. The Storm finished the
game with a season-low seven turnovers and held a 40-19 rebounding
edge.

The next game for both teams is September 1. Seattle will be
home to face Sacramento, while Charlotte plays Connecticut at home.
